// Coverity Security Directives for MongoDB — C/C++ analysis
//
// Passed to cov-analyze via: --directive-file etc/coverity_models/mongo_security_directives.json
//
// ============================================================================
// CURRENT STATUS: PLACEHOLDER — SEE LIMITATION NOTES BELOW
// ============================================================================
//
// Security Directives support for C-like (C/C++/Objective-C) in Coverity
// 2025.6.0 is severely constrained:
//
//   SUPPORTED for C-like (format_version 12):
//     - dc_checker_name / method_set_for_dc_checker
//       (deprecated DC.CUSTOM_CHECKER — flags calls to named methods, no
//        data-flow tracking)
//
//   NOT SUPPORTED for C-like (Java-only):
//     - sink_for_checker      — verified: parse error in C-like context
//     - simple_entry_point    — taint sources
//     - method_returns_tainted_data — taint sources
//     - sensitive_operation   — sink patterns
//     - All other taint directives
//
// CONSEQUENCE FOR CVE-2025-14847 CLASS:
//   There is no Security Directives mechanism to add custom TAINTED_SCALAR
//   sources for C/C++. The CompressionHeader constructor (reads from network
//   wire → sets uncompressedSize) cannot be declared as a taint source via
//   this file. The sink (SharedBuffer::allocate) also cannot be registered as
//   a TAINTED_SCALAR sink for C/C++.
//
//   Full custom source+sink taint tracking for C/C++ requires CodeXM —
//   Coverity's Scala-based checker SDK. That is the recommended path for
//   this class of vulnerability going forward.
//
// WHAT THIS FILE PROVIDES:
//   A minimal valid C-like directive that flags ALL calls to
//   SharedBuffer::allocate as DC.CUSTOM_UNCHECKED_ALLOC_SIZE findings,
//   regardless of whether arguments are tainted. This is blunt (catches
//   safe calls too) but ensures the function at minimum appears in Coverity
//   findings for manual review when a new callsite is introduced.
//
//   Remove or disable this if the DC.CUSTOM_UNCHECKED_ALLOC_SIZE finding
//   count grows unmanageable; it is a stopgap until CodeXM source tracking
//   is implemented.
//
// References:
//   src/mongo/util/shared_buffer.h — SharedBuffer::allocate(size_t, Allocator={})
//   Coverity Security Directives Reference 2025.6.0 — dc_checker_name
//   Coverity Checker Reference 2025.6.0 — DC.CUSTOM_CHECKER, CodeXM
{
  "type": "Coverity analysis configuration",
  "format_version": 12,
  "language": "C-like",
  "directives": [
    // Define a custom DC checker that fires on any call to SharedBuffer::allocate.
    // NOTE: This is NOT taint-driven. It fires on ALL calls, not just those
    // receiving untrusted input. Treat findings as "requires manual review of
    // bounds checking" rather than confirmed vulnerabilities.
    { "dc_checker_name": "DC.CUSTOM_UNCHECKED_ALLOC_SIZE" },
    {
      "method_set_for_dc_checker": "DC.CUSTOM_UNCHECKED_ALLOC_SIZE",
      "methods": { "named": "mongo::SharedBuffer::allocate" },
      "txt_defect_message": "SharedBuffer::allocate() called — verify the size argument is bounds-checked against a trusted maximum before allocation (cf. CVE-2025-14847 class of vulnerability)."
    }
  ]
}
